&gt; On Jun 1, 2010, at 6:43 AM, Glenn Block wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Aside from the specification / documentation for a media type is there
&gt; some common accepted practice for indicating which media type is expected to
&gt; passed when calling a link?
&gt;
&gt; What do you mean by &#39;calling a link&#39;?
&gt;
&gt; If you mean: &#39;submitting data via a PUT or POST request&#39; then the usual
&gt; means by which the server informs the client about what media types it is
&gt; capable of processing is some information contained in the corresponding
&gt; form.
&gt;
&gt; Examples are
&gt;
&gt; HTML&#39;s form enctype attribute on the &lt;form&gt; element
&gt; AtomPub&#39;s &lt;accept&gt; element inside the &lt;collection&gt; element[1]
&gt; OpenSearch&#39;s &lt;parameters:enctype&gt; attribute on the &lt;Url&gt; element[2]
&gt;
&gt; Jan
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; [1] http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5023#section-8.3.4
